## Implementation Details

The Analytics component is placed in the optimal position:
```tsx
const App = () => (
  <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
    <TooltipProvider>
      <PersistenceProvider>
        <UserPreferencesProvider>
          <DashboardProvider>
            <Toaster />
            <Sonner />
            <BrowserRouter>
              <AppRoutes />
            </BrowserRouter>
            <Analytics /> {/* ← Properly positioned for tracking */}
          </DashboardProvider>
        </UserPreferencesProvider>
      </PersistenceProvider>
    </TooltipProvider>
  </QueryClientProvider>
);
```

## Next Steps for Usage

To use this implementation on Vercel:

1. **Enable Web Analytics in Vercel Dashboard**
   - Go to your project in Vercel Dashboard
   - Click the "Analytics" tab
   - Click "Enable" to activate Web Analytics

2. **Deploy to Vercel**
   - Run `vercel deploy` or push to connected Git repository
   - After deployment, the `/_vercel/insights/*` routes will be available

3. **Verify Tracking**
   - Visit your deployed site
   - Check browser Network tab for requests to `/_vercel/insights/view`
   - These requests confirm tracking is working

4. **View Analytics Data**
   - Go to Vercel Dashboard → Your Project → Analytics tab
   - Data will start appearing after visitors access the site

## Notes

- The implementation is production-ready
- Route changes are automatically tracked via React Router
- No additional configuration needed in the code
- Analytics only sends data when deployed to Vercel (not in local development by default)
